    <!-- FAQ -->
    <section class="faq-sec">
      <h2>Plant-Based Gummy Candy — Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
      <details class="fq"><summary>What is plant-based gummy candy?</summary><p>Plant-based gummy candy uses pectin, agar-agar, or starch instead of animal-derived gelatin. It excludes beeswax, carmine, shellac, and other animal ingredients. "Plant-based" is functionally interchangeable with "vegan" in the candy context.</p></details>
      <details class="fq"><summary>What types of plant-based candy are available?</summary><p>Gummy bears, sour worms, rings, fruit snacks, fruit strips, chocolate bars, peanut butter cups, hard candy, lollipops, licorice, caramels, and more. Virtually every candy type now has a plant-based option.</p></details>
      <details class="fq"><summary>Is plant-based candy healthier than regular candy?</summary><p>It depends on the brand. SmartSweets (3g sugar) is much healthier than Haribo (34g sugar). But some plant-based brands have comparable sugar. The consistent advantage is no synthetic dyes or artificial flavors.</p></details>
      <details class="fq"><summary>What popular candy brands are NOT plant-based?</summary><p>Haribo (gelatin + beeswax), Trolli (gelatin), Starburst (gelatin), Reese's (dairy). Swedish Fish, Sour Patch Kids, and Skittles are debated due to beeswax, bone char sugar processing, or shellac.</p></details>
      <details class="fq"><summary>Are Skittles plant-based?</summary><p>Skittles are gelatin-free but may contain bone char-processed sugar and shellac (confectioner's glaze) depending on the market. Strict vegans typically avoid them.</p></details>
      <details class="fq"><summary>What makes gummy candy not vegan?</summary><p>Gelatin (animal collagen), beeswax (glazing agent), carmine/E120 (insect-derived red dye), shellac (insect secretion coating), and potentially bone char-processed sugar.</p></details>
      <details class="fq"><summary>Where is the best place to buy plant-based candy?</summary><p>Amazon (widest selection, best multi-pack pricing), Whole Foods (largest in-store selection), Target and Walmart (mainstream brands), Trader Joe's (house brands), Sprouts (niche organic brands).</p></details>
      <details class="fq"><summary>Is plant-based candy more expensive than regular candy?</summary><p>Premium brands (SmartSweets: $3.49) cost 2-3x more. Value brands (Black Forest: $0.99, YumEarth: $1.29) are price-competitive with mainstream candy. Multi-packs on Amazon narrow the gap further.</p></details>
    </section>

